25 PROJECT LOCATIONS MAXIMUM CAP A CITIES MINIMUM INSURANCE REQUIREMENTS FOR MANAGER -11- LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT This LGIA CO-TENANCY AGREEMENT (this "Agreement") is made and entered into as of November 20, 2015, by and among RE Garland LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Garland"), in its individual capacity, RE Garland A LLC, a Delaware limited liability company ("Garland A" and, together with Garland, each individually a "Co-Tenant" and collectively the "Co-Tenants"), and Garland in its capacity as Manager hereunder. RECITALS A. The Co-Tenants are developing and will construct, own and operate a series of solar energy projects with a maximum aggregate capacity of 200 MW located in the unincorporated area of North Antelope Valley, Kern County, California in the locations shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. B. Each Co-Tenant will construct, own and operate its respective Project (as defined herein), including photovoltaic panels, current inverters and other assets, but will jointly own and share, the rights and obligations under the LGIA (as defined herein), as tenants in common. C. The Co-Tenants, as tenants-in-common, have entered into that certain Large Generator Interconnection Agreement by and among the Co-Tenants, Southern California Edison Company ("SCE") and the California Independent System Operator Corporation (the "CAISO"), dated as of May 15, 2015, as amended as of October 19, 2015 and as may be further amended from time-to-time, together with all agreements, schedules, appendices, exhibits and other documents ancillary thereto (the "LGIA") for the purpose of securing interconnection rights for each of the Projects. D. The Co-Tenants will own, together with RE Astoria LLC ("Astoria"), RE Astoria 2 LLC ("Astoria"), and RE Garland 2 LLC ("Garland 2" and, together with Astoria and Astoria 2, the "Gen-Tie Entities") a pro rata share, in proportion to the nominal capacity (in MW) of their respective project as it relates to the combined capacity of the all projects (such capacity being 500 MW at the Point of Interconnection) delivering energy to the Point of Interconnection (as defined in the LGIA), in and to certain generator tie-line, switchyard and related facilities (the "Shared Facilities"), pursuant to a separate agreement (the "Shared Facilities Agreement") entered into by and among the Co-Tenants and the Gen-Tie Entities. E. The Co-Tenants desire to enter into this Agreement to set forth the terms and conditions under which they will be co-tenants under the LGIA and share the LGIA among themselves and their Projects, to designate Garland as the "Manager" under the LGIA in order to administer and manage the Co-Tenants' rights and obligations under the LGIA with respect to CAISO and the Participating TO, and certain other related matters. NOW, THEREFORE, in consideration of the foregoing and the agreements and covenants contained herein, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which are hereby acknowledged, the Parties hereto agree as follows: -1- AGREEMENT ARTICLE I DEFINITIONS 1.1 Certain Definitions. Capitalized words and phrases used herein shall have the following meanings, or the meanings given in the Sections of this Agreement in which they are defined, unless the text expressly or by necessary implication requires otherwise. "Control" means the possession, directly or indirectly, of the power to direct or cause the direction of the management or policies of a Person, whether through the ownership of voting -2- securities, its capacity as sole or managing member, its capacity as general partner, by contract or otherwise. The term "Control" when used as a verb shall have a correlative meaning. "Co-Tenant" and "Co-Tenants" have the meanings given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Co-Tenant Representative" has the meaning given in Section 7 .12. "Curtailed Output Cap" has the meaning given in Section 2.4(c)(ii). "Defaulting Party" has the meaning given in Section 5 .1. "Dispute" has the meaning given in Section 5.4(a). "Distribution Upgrades" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Effective Date" shall be the date established by FERC in its order accepting the Agreement for filing. "Emergency Condition" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Event of Default" has the meaning given in Section 5 .1. "FERC" means the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission or any successor agency. "Financing Party" means any and all lenders (including the U.S. Department of Energy, as a loan guarantor, and the "owner lessor" or similar entity in a lease financing) providing senior or subordinated construction, interim or long-term debt financing or refinancing (including hedging counterparties) for the development, construction, purchase or operation of a Project and any trustee or agent acting on behalf of any such lenders; provided, however, that the Co-Tenants may agree by separate written agreement or instrument that another Person shall have the rights of a "Financing Party" hereunder. "Force Majeure" means (i) with respect to the LGIA and the Interconnection Facilities, "Force Majeure" as defined in the LGIA, and (ii) in all other cases, any act, casualty or occurrence, condition, event or circumstance of any kind or nature not reasonably within the excused party's control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures, including: (A) acts of God or the elements (including fire, earthquake, explosion, flood, epidemic or any other similar casualty or accident) or condemnation; (B) strikes, lock outs or other labor disputes (unless the strike, lock out or labor dispute is directed solely against the party claiming the Force Majeure ); (C) the failure or inability to obtain permits and other governmental authorizations for reasons not within the excused party's control and which could not have been avoided by reasonable measures; and (D) war, terrorism, sabotage, civil strife or other violence. Force Majeure expressly does not include late delivery or breakage of equipment or materials or economic hardship except to the extent caused by a Force Majeure event. "FPA" has the meaning given in Section 2.9(a). -3- "Garland" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Garland Project" means the solar energy electric generating facility to be developed, owned and operated by Garland (or its successor or permitted assign) with a Maximum Capacity of 180 MW at the Point oflnterconnection, in the location shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. "Garland A" has the meaning given in the preamble to this Agreement. "Garland A Project" means the solar energy electric generating facility to be developed, owned and operated by Garland A (or its successor or permitted assign), with a Maximum Capacity of 20 MW at the Point of Interconnection, in the location shown on Exhibit A attached hereto. "Garland 2" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "Gen-Tie Entities" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "General Default Cure Period" has the meaning given in Section 5. I. "Good Utility Practice" has the meaning given in the LOIA. "Indemnified Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 2.7(a). "Indemnifying Co-Tenant" has the meaning given in Section 2. 7(a). "Interconnection Customer" has the meaning given in the LOIA. "Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LOIA. "Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LOIA. "Interest Rate" means the lesser of (a) the prime rate as published in "The Money Rates" Section of The Wall Street Journal (U.S. Edition), plus five percent (5%) per annum and (b) the highest rate permitted under Applicable Laws and Regulations. "LOIA" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "LOIA Costs" means (i) all amounts.due and payable under the LOIA, including amounts payable to CAISO or the Participating TO, and (ii) all costs and expenses necessary or appropriate for the Manager to incur or pay in connection with administering and managing the LOIA, including in connection with affirmative covenants with respect to maintenance of the Interconnection Customer's Interconnection Facilities, communications with CAISO, insurance and reporting. "Manager" means initially Garland, in its capacity as "Manager" under the LOIA, any subsequent Person appointed as Manager pursuant to this Agreement, and their respective successors and permitted assigns. -4- "Manager Representative" has the meaning given in Section 7.13. "Maximum Capacity" means, in respect of the Garland Project, a design capacity of 180 MW and, in respect of the Garland A Project, a design capacity of 20 MW, in each case as measured at the Point of Interconnection and which, when combined with the Maximum Capacity of the other Project, shall not exceed 200 MW net output at the Point of Interconnection, as identified and described in Appendix C to the LGIA, and summarized on Exhibit B, which Maximum Capacity may be changed only in accordance with Section 2.6. Without prejudice to the immediately preceding sentence, a Project's nameplate or nominal capacity may be greater than its Maximum Capacity. · "MW" means a megawatt or megawatts AC, as the context may require. "NERC" means the North American Electric Reliability Corporation or its successor organization. "Network Upgrades" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Notice of Dispute" has the meaning given in Section 5.4(a). "Participating TO" has the meaning given in the LGIA. The Parties agree that the Participating TO is SCE. "Participating TO's Interconnection Facilities" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Party" means either of the Co-Tenants or the Manager. "Payment Default Cure Period" has the meaning given in Section 5 .1. "Percentage Interest" means, 90 percent with respect to Garland, and 10 percent with respect to Garland A. "Person" means any individual or entity, and the heirs, personal representatives, successors and assigns of such individual or entity where the context so permits. "Point of Interconnection" has the meaning given in the LGIA. "Project" means each of the Garland Project and the Garland A Project. "Project Controlled Assets" means, for each Co-Tenant, any of the assets comprising its respective Project, the corresponding Project Real Property and related Project agreements and contractual arrangements. For the avoidance of doubt, the Project Controlled Assets exclude the LGIA. "Project Real Property" means, for either Project, the real property interests utilized by such Project. "SCE" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. -5- "Shared Facilities" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "Shared Facilities Agreement" has the meaning given in the recitals to this Agreement. "Shortfall" has the meaning given in Section 2.4(c)(ii). "Transfer" ineans, with respect to any asset, the sale, assignment, transfer, pledge, encumbrance, transfer, or other disposition of such asset. "Transferee" shall be interpreted accordingly. "Undivided Interest" has the meaning given in Section 2.1. "WECC" means the Western Electricity Coordinating Council or its successor organization. 1.2 Rules of Construction. Except where expressly provided or unless the context necessarily requires otherwise, (a) all references in this Agreement to a given Article, Section, Subsection, clause or Exhibit is a reference to an Article, Section, Subsection, clause or Exhibit of this Agreement, (b) the terms "hereof', "herein", "hereto", "hereunder" and "herewith" refer to this Agreement as a whole, ( c) references in this Agreement to a given agreement, instrument, document or Law is a reference to that agreement, instrument, document or Law as modified, amended, supplemented and restated from time to time, ( d) "includes" or "including" means "including without limitation", ( e) references in this Agreement to "days" means calendar days unless Business Days are specified; and (f) all personal pronouns, whether masculine, feminine or neuter, include all other genders, the singular includes the plural, and the plural includes the singular. ARTICLE II CO-TENANCY RIGHTS AND OBLIGATIONS 2.1 Dedaration of Intention. The Parties hereby declare that their relationship in and to the LGIA and the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations thereunder is and will be that of tenants-in-common, and that each Co-Tenant will have an undivided interest ("Undivided Interest") in the LGIA and the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations thereunder, expressly subject, however, to the terms, conditions, limitations and requirements set forth in this Agreement. Nothing contained in this Agreement will be deemed to constitute the Parties as partners or joint venturers. The Parties acknowledge and agree that the Garland Project and the Garland A Project will be treated as a single Project under the LGIA and that there can be no more than two co-tenants under the LGIA without the consent of CAISO and the Participating TO. 2.2 Use of LGIA. The LGIA shall be held and used solely to permit the interconnection of the Projects to the CAISO Controlled Grid and to deliver electricity and electricity-related products generated or otherwise made available by the respective Projects owned by each Co-Tenant (or by such Co-Tenant's successors or permitted assigns) at the Point -6- of Interconnection. No Co-Tenant may use or permit the use of the LGIA in a manner that would reasonably be expected to interfere with the use and enjoyment by the other Co-Tenant of such Co-Tenant's Project, or to violate Applicable Laws and Regulations; provided that a CoTenant's use of the LGIA in compliance with this Agreement shall be deemed to not interfere with any other Co-Tenant's use and enjoyment of its Project. In the event of a conflict between the terms of the LGIA and this Agreement, the terms of the LGIA shall prevail. 2.3 Maximum Capacity. No Co-Tenant shall interconnect its respective Project to the Point of Interconnection to the extent the installed capacity of such Project exceeds its Maximum Capacity at the Point oflnterconnection. To the extent that conditions exist which result in a CoTenant delivering energy to the Point of Interconnection from its respective Project in excess of the Maximum Capacity in respect of such Project, then such Co-Tenant shall at its expense immediately curtail the operation of its Project so as not to exceed its Maximum Capacity. 2.4 Curtailment. (a) The Manager may, in accordance with this Section 2.4, direct the Co- Tenants to interrupt or reduce deliveries of electrical power (i) with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), when necessary in order to maintain, repair, replace, remove, investigate, inspect or test any part of either Project; (ii) if the Manager determines, in its reasonable discretion, that interruption or reduction is necessary due to an Emergency Condition; or (iii) at the direction of the Participating TO or the CAISO pursuant to rights under the LGIA. Manager will use commercially reasonable efforts io give the CoTenants as much advance notice as is reasonably possible for interruptions, reductions or curtailments under this clause (a). (b) With respect to any interruption or reduction of deliveries of electrical power pursuant to clauses (i) or (ii) of Section 2.4(a), the Manager shall limit the length and quantity of any such interruption or curtailment to the minimum extent and minimum time strictly necessary to correct the problem. Any interruption or curtailment made pursuant to clause (i) of Section 2.4(a) shall be made consistent with Good Utility Practice and to the extent commercially reasonable during periods of low or no solar generation or low energy prices. ( c) In the event of any curtailment of interconnection services at the direction . of CAISO or Participating TO, subject to Section 2.4(d), such curtailment shall be allocated in the following manner until such curtailment is achieved: (i) first, each Co-Tenant (if any) that is delivering energy in excess of such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity shall reduce deliveries down to such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity, (ii) second, each Co-Tenant that 1s delivering test power shall reduce all such deliveries down to zero, (iii) third, as provided in and to the extent applicable under Sections 2.4(d)(ii) below, until all such curtailments have been applied or either or both Co-Tenants have been fully curtailed; and -7- (iv) fourth, subject to Section 2.4(d)(i) below, to the extent it has not already been fully curtailed, each Co-Tenant shall reduce its energy deliveries so that they do not exceed an amount (the "Curtailed Output Cap") equal to (X) such Co-Tenant's Maximum Capacity, minus (Y) the product of(!) the aggregate number of MW then required for the combined Projects to curtail (after application of preceding clause (i)) times (2) such CoTenant's Percentage Interest; provided, further, that if during any relevant period of curtailment any Co-Tenant is delivering energy at a level less than its Curtailed Output Cap (any such amount, a "Shortfall") either because such Co-Tenant's Project is undergoing maintenance, has a forced outage, or other circumstance, then for so long as such Shortfall exists, the Manager shall use reasonable efforts to authorize the other Co-Tenant to generate above such Co-Tenant's Curtailed Output Cap. · (d) Notwithstanding the other provisions of this Section 2.4: (i) The Manager (with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), in the case of curtailments under Section 2.4(a)(i)) shall curtail on a non-pro rata, but equitable and reasonable basis (as determined by the Manager in good faith) if (A) in spite of the Manager's good faith efforts to direct the Co-Tenants to comply with this Section 2.4, curtailment of interconnection services directed by the CAISO or Participating TO is not otherwise achievable, or (B) such non-pro rata allocation is otherwise necessary to comply with the LGIA or CAISO or Participating TO direction, and, in each of the foregoing clauses (A) and (B), that such non-pro rata allocation will not result in a default under the LGIA; and (ii) To the extent that the need for any curtailment, interruption or reduction can be attributed to a particular Co-Tenant's Project or portions of its Project or the failure of such Project to comply with the order to curtail or a default by such Co-Tenant under the LGIA or an applicable power purchase agreement, or to the extent such Co-Tenant's Project is the cause of an Emergency Condition, then all such curtailment shall be allocated first to such Co-Tenant and such Co-Tenant will be responsible for all costs, liabilities, and damages resulting from such curtailment (subject to the limitations in this Agreement) and the Manager shall, to the extent possible, limit such interruption or reduction to such Project or such portions of the Project, as the case may be. (e) Each Co-Tenant shall promptly effect such interruption in, or reduction of, delivery as the Manager shall direct pursuant to this Section 2.4 (with the prior consent of all of the Co-Tenants (not including any Defaulting Party), in the case of curtailments under Section 2.4(a)(i)) upon notice from the Manager. In the event notice is impracticable or a Co-Tenant fails to promptly comply therewith, the Manager may effect the same by direct action; A CoTenant that fails to implement any such curtailment, interruption or reduction, shall be responsible for all cost and expenses related thereto, including deviation or imbalance charges and penalties assessed by the CAISO. 2.5 Shared Expenses. Each Co-Tenant hereby confirms its obligation to share in the payment of all costs, charges and expenses incurred in connection with the LGIA in accordance with the following provisions including, without limitation, the cost of construction of -8- Interconnection Facilities and Network Upgrades and Interconnection Facilities Charges (and all ongoing costs associated with such facilities): (a) LGIA Costs. As between themselves (but without limiting each Co- Tenant's rights with regard to contributions from other entities, including the Gen-Tie Entities, under any other agreements including the Shared Facilities Agreement), each Co-Tenant shall be responsible for the payment of its pro rata share of the LGIA Costs in proportion to such CoTenant's Percentage Interest. Such payment shall be paid when due to Manager, and Manager shall pay such amount to the applicable parties, unless Manager requests that each Co-Tenant pay any LGIA Costs due to CAISO or the Participating TO directly, in which case each CoTenant shall pay such LGIA Costs to CAISO and/or the Participating TO directly in proportion to such Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest. In either case, each Co-Tenant shall pay its share of LGIA Costs without regard to whether such Co-Tenant has issued a notice to proceed with construction of its Project prior to the date such payment is due to CAISO or the Participating TO. Notwithstanding anything to the contrary herein, any capital expenditures arising out of any equipment or facilities solely required to interconnect a particular Project shall be the sole responsibility of such Project and its Co" Tenant. (b) Collection and Payment ofLGIA Costs. The Manager shall, as authorized representative for each Co-Tenant, administer the collection, payment and reimbursement of the LGIA Costs and other amounts relating to the performance of the Interconnection Customer's rights and obligations under the LGIA, including amounts due to or from the Interconnection Customer under or in connection with the LGIA. The Manager shall be responsible for invoicing the Co-Tenants their respective shares of such LGIA Costs and providing backup documentation for such invoices. The Manager shall establish procedures for invoicing and collecting payments from Co-Tenants in order to enable Manager to timely collect and pay for LGIA Costs and to enable Manager and Co-Tenants to achieve the payment requirements under and in connection with the LGIA. Each Co-Tenant shallhave the right to audit, and receive periodic supporting documentation for, any expenses or other amounts required to be paid by such Co-Tenant hereunder. (c) To the extent that the Manager receives any damages, credits or refunds pursuant to the LOIA, the Manager shall promptly remit such damages, credits or refunds to the Co-Tenants according to each Co-Tenant's Percentage Interest (unless such damages, credits or refunds accrue to a specific Co-Tenant, in which event the Manager shall promptly remit them to such Co-Tenant). 2.6 Changes in Maximum Capacity. (a) The Maximum Capacity of either Project shall be increased only upon receipt by such Project's Co-Tenant of (i) written consent to such increase provided by the other Co-Tenant, such consent to be provided in each such Co-Tenant's sole discretion, (ii) all consents required under the Shared Facilities Agreement, (iii) an executed and effective new or amended LGIA that reflects the increase in Maximum Capacity and (iv) any other necessary consents by CAISO and the Participating TO. -9- (b) The Maximum Capacity of either Project shall be decreased only upon receipt by such Project's Co-Tenant of written consent to such decrease provided by (i) CAISO and the Participating TO, and (ii) the other Co-Tenant, such consent not to be unreasonably withheld;. provided however, that any such decrease in Maximum Capacity shall not decrease or change such Co-Tenant's responsibility for payment of Shared Expenses based on its initial Percentage Interest based on such Project's initial Maximum Capacity as set forth on Exhibit B hereto, including payment ofLGIA Costs under Section 2.5. 2.7 Indemnity. (a) Subject to the limitations provided in Section 7.11, each Co-Tenant (an "Indemnifying Co-Tenant") shall indemnify, defend and hold harmless the other Co-Tenant (an "Indemnified Co-Tenant") and the Manager from and against any and all losses, damages, liabilities, claims, judgments, liens, penalties, costs and expenses, including, without limitation, reasonable attorneys' and consultants' fees (collectively, "Claims"), which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Indemnified Co-Tenant or Manager or asserted against such Indemnified Co-Tenant or Manager as a result of any breach by the Indemnifying Co-Tenant of this Agreement or the LGIA (including, without limitation, to the extent so imposed or incurred as the result of joint liability under the LGIA), or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant or in connection with the ownership, use, operation, maintenance or repair of the Indemnifying Co-Tenant's Project. (b) Subject to the limitations provided in Sections 3.3(c) and 7.11, the Manager shall indemnify, defend, and hold harmless the Co-Tenants from any Claims which may be (i) imposed upon or incurred by such Co-Tenants as a result of gross negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager, or (ii) incurred by third parties in respect of loss of, or damage to, property or injury to, or death of, persons, as a result of negligence, fraud or willful misconduct of the Manager. 2.8 Taxes. Each Co-Tenant shall pay all real and personal property taxes and assessments, general or special, levied against its Project, including any taxes and assessments levied against such Co-Tenant's Undivided Interest in the LGIA, except for any taxes or assessments that are LGIA Costs or that are paid pursuant to the Shared Facilities Agreement. All such taxes and assessments shall be paid before delinquency and before any fine, interest or penalty shall become due or be imposed for their non-payment; provided however, that each CoTenant retains its rights under applicable law to seek a refund of such taxes and assessments after having paid them. 2.9 Operation and Management; Insurance. (a) Each Co-Tenant shall operate and maintain its Project Controlled Assets acting as a prudent operator and manager and otherwise (a) in accordance with the terms of the LGIA, (b) in accordance with Good Utility Practice, (c) in compliance with all Applicable Laws and Regulations, including but not limited to the Federal Power Act, as amended ("FPA"), all rules, regulations, and orders issued by the FERC pursuant to the FP A, and all laws and -10- regulations relating to land use, hazardous substances and environmental protection, ( d) in compliance with the CAISO Tariff, including the rules, protocols, procedures and standards attached thereto, as the same may be amended from time to time and approved by FERC, (e) in compliance with the rules, protocols, procedures and standards of NERC and WECC, and (f) without causing a material adverse effect on the LOIA. (b) Each Co-Tenant shall comply with its obligations under the LOIA, · including with respect to its obligations to fund LOIA Costs arising under the LOIA. Each CoTenant shall be an "exempt wholesale generator" as such term is defined in the Public Utility Holding Company Act of2005. (c) Each Co-Tenant shall cooperate with and timely respond to the Manager as a representative for the Co-Tenants under the LOIA, and shall provide the Manager such information, certifications and other matters as may be required to comply with the obligations under the LOIA. ( d) Each Co-Tenant shall ma\ntain insurance in accordance with the requirements of the LOIA. The Manager shall maintain insurance in accordance with the requirements of Exhibit C hereto. 2.10 Joint and Several Liability. Notwithstanding any other provision hereof, each CoTenant acknowledges and agrees that under the LOIA it is jointly and severally liable for (i) any payments due under the LOIA imposed on the Interconnection Customer and (ii) the performance of the obligations and duties imposed on the Interconnection Customer by the LOIA; provided that a Co-Tenant's joint and several liability under the LOIA shall not diminish or impair any Co-Tenant's rights to reimbursement or contribution from another Co-Tenant or any other Person hereunder or under any other agreement, including the Shared Facilities Agreement. RE GARLAND A LLC MARKET-BASED RATE TARIFF
1. Availability: RE Garland A LLC ("Seller") makes electric energy, capacity and ancillary services available under this Tariff, except as prohibited below.
2. Applicability: This Tariff is applicable to all wholesale sales of energy, capacity, and ancillary services by Seller, which are (1) subject to the jurisdiction of the Commission, and (b) not made pursuant to another tariff on file with the Commission.
3. Rates: All sales shall be made at rates established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and Seller.
5. Seller Category: Seller is a Category 2 seller in the Southwest region, as defined in 18 C.F.R. ? 35.36(a), and a Category 1 seller in the Northwest, Central, Southwest Power Pool, Northeast, and Southeast regions.
6. Compliance with Commission Regulations: Seller shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes Seller to engage in affiliate sales under this Tariff or otherwise restricts or limits Seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning Seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this Tariff.
7. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: Seller has received waiver of: Subparts B and C of Part 35, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15 and 35.16; Part 41, Part 101 (with the exception that waiver of the provisions of Part 101 that apply to hydropower licensees has not been granted with respect to licensed hydropower projects), and Part 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15; and received blanket approval under Part 34. RE Garland A LLC, Docket No. ER16-706-000 (2016). Seller is subject to restrictions on sales of energy set forth in Southern Company Services, Inc., FERC Electric Tariff Second Revised Volume No. 4 that prohibit certain market-based energy sales for delivery at a point in the Southern Balancing Authority Area during auction bid periods specified under the Southern Company Energy Auction, as accepted in Southern Company Services, Inc., 125 FERC ? 61,317 (2008). See Southern Company Services, Inc., 129 FERC ? 61,222 at P 8 (2009).
8. Ancillary Services: Seller may make available to any purchaser the following ancillary services:
California: Seller offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO.
Third-party ancillary services: Seller offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization.
9. Effective Date: This Tariff is effective on such date as set by the Commission. 1
